<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
	<!--
		Privacy manifest for the NALI Migraine Log iOS bundle.

		Apple's tooling expects exactly one PrivacyInfo.xcprivacy per .app
		bundle, so each target gets its own copy. Synchronized root groups
		only auto-include `.xcprivacy` files in their owning target — they
		do NOT propagate the file to other targets that also consume the
		same root group — so co-locating one file in `NALI Migraine Log/`
		would silently leave the macOS and watchOS bundles missing their
		manifest. Three separate files, one per primary synchronized root,
		is the only configuration that produces the expected output.

		Sibling files that MUST stay in lockstep when adding a new
		required-reason API anywhere in the codebase:

		  - NALI Migraine Log/PrivacyInfo.xcprivacy            (this file)
		  - NALI Migraine Log macOS/PrivacyInfo.xcprivacy
		  - NALI Migraine Log Watch App Watch App/PrivacyInfo.xcprivacy

		Apple does not allow under-declaration; over-declaration is
		harmless. The iOS file lists the most surface area because that
		target also surfaces the recovery-file UI, which reads file
		modification timestamps. macOS and Watch list only what they
		actually use.

		Tracking
		--------
		We do not link any data collected by this app with data collected
		by other companies' apps, websites, or properties. All migraine,
		weather, and HealthKit data either stays on-device or is synced
		exclusively through the user's own iCloud account via
		NSPersistentCloudKitContainer. NSPrivacyTracking is therefore
		set to false. Per Apple's TN3181, when tracking is false the
		NSPrivacyTrackingDomains key MUST be omitted entirely (an empty
		array there triggers ITMS-91056 at App Store submission time).

		Data collection
		---------------
		We do not collect data and send it to a server we control. iCloud
		sync uses the user's own private CloudKit database. The watch app
		additionally relays new entries to the paired iPhone via
		WatchConnectivity, but that is a peer-to-peer hand-off, not
		developer-side data collection. Because we collect nothing, the
		NSPrivacyCollectedDataTypes key is also omitted entirely; an
		empty array there has likewise been reported to trigger
		ITMS-91056. If we ever start collecting data, add the key back
		with one or more populated dictionaries — never as an empty
		array.

		Required-reason API declarations
		--------------------------------
		Each entry below uses Apple's published reason codes
		(https://developer.apple.com/documentation/bundleresources/
		describing_use_of_required_reason_api).
	-->
	<key>NSPrivacyTracking</key>
	<false/>
	<key>NSPrivacyAccessedAPITypes</key>
	<array>
		<dict>
			<!--
				UserDefaults — used by every target to persist app
				settings, the disclaimer acceptance flag, the
				MigrationCoordinator's last-launched-version stamp,
				the data-migration completion flag, and the path to a
				moved-aside Core Data store after a recovery. All values
				are read and written exclusively by this app.
			-->
			<key>NSPrivacyAccessedAPIType</key>
			<string>NSPrivacyAccessedAPICategoryUserDefaults</string>
			<key>NSPrivacyAccessedAPITypeReasons</key>
			<array>
				<string>CA92.1</string>
			</array>
		</dict>
		<dict>
			<!--
				File timestamp — read via FileManager.attributesOfItem(atPath:)
				inside SettingsView's recovery section to display the
				modification date of a moved-aside Core Data store so
				the user can confirm which backup they're about to share
				with support. Timestamps are shown in the UI and never
				sent off-device or used to derive other signals. The
				macOS and watchOS bundles do not surface this UI today,
				so their manifests omit this entry — re-add it there if
				the recovery surface is ever ported across platforms.
			-->
			<key>NSPrivacyAccessedAPIType</key>
			<string>NSPrivacyAccessedAPICategoryFileTimestamp</string>
			<key>NSPrivacyAccessedAPITypeReasons</key>
			<array>
				<string>C617.1</string>
			</array>
		</dict>
	</array>
</dict>
</plist>
